uthorship in the representation of gender and ethnicity. Foregrounding such issues as the quest for identity, the negotiation of space and the recourse to memory and history, she argues that these films challenge and reframe the symbolic spaces of French culture, addressing issues of ethnicity and difference which are central to today's debates about what it means to be French. This timely book is essential reading for anyone interested in the relationship between cinema and citizenship in a multicultural society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszFrance. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory. 0aRace in motion pictures. 0aRealism in motion pictures. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2019. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAlgerian filmmakers.  aAmeur-Zaifmeche.  aFrench film industry.  aLe Raïd.  aMaghrebi descent.  acinéma beur.  acinéma de banlieue.  afilmmaking practices.  amulti-ethnic society.  awhite filmmakers.1 aTarr, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614175040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526141750423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526141750/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles